properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: First significant snowfall of the season Thursday night into Friday. A intensifying low pressure system will approach Ontario from the southwest. Snow may arrive by Thursday evening then continue through the night before tapering off by Friday afternoon. Snowfall amounts near 10 cm are possible. Motorists should be prepared for poor winter driving conditions, and adjust travel plans accordingly. There is some uncertainty in the track of this low pressure system and the amount of snowfall expected. This event will continue to be closely monitored. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A couple of significant snowfall events expected. Total snowfall: 5 to 10 cm between Thursday afternoon and Friday morning. 10 to possibly in excess of 25 cm between Friday afternoon and Saturday morning. Maximum wind gusts: 70 km/h or higher Friday night. Locations: Along the coast from Rigolet to Lodge Bay, and all of the interior for the first snow event. Along the coast from Hopedale to Cartwright as well as the interior from Labrador City and Wabush to Upper Lake Melville for the second snow event. Timespan: Thursday afternoon to Friday morning for the first snow event. Friday afternoon to Saturday morning for the second event. Remarks: Snow is expected for a large portion of Labrador beginning Thursday afternoon through to Friday morning and again beginning on Friday afternoon or evening. The snowfall on Friday night is expected to be the more intense and significant of the two events and be accompanied by high winds. Conditions will improve on Saturday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Summary:

This weather system will bring a significant rainfall with it tonight through Thursday with many areas receiving a total of 20 to 40 mm of rain by Thursday evening. Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. The ground, already near saturation, has little ability to absorb further rainfall. A total of 50 to 80 millimetres of rain is expected over these regions by Friday morning. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A wet Halloween with significant rain expected. Rain will fall tonight and Thursday then through Friday afternoon. Rainfall amounts of 30 to 50 mm are possible, with the heaviest rain likely Thursday evening. In addition to the rainfall, strong northwesterly to westerly wind gusts of 70 km/h are possible Friday morning into Friday afternoon. If visibility is reduced during driving, turn on headlights and maintain a safe following distance. Remember pedestrians are more difficult to see when it is dark and raining. A low pressure system approaching Southern Ontario from the southwest is responsible for the wet and blustery weather. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-31T18:20:08-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rain expected for New Brunswick today and Friday... A low pressure system will approach the Maritimes from the west today. Rain ahead of this system is expected to persist into Friday. Most areas will see rainfall in the range of 30 to 50 mm, however some areas could see locally higher amounts. Southern and extreme northwestern areas of the province are expected to receive the most rain and rainfall warnings are in effect for these areas. The public is advised to monitor future forecasts as additional warnings may be required. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.
